subanswer.text:
Tool usage among different species often depends on their physical abilities, cognitive capabilities, environmental needs, as well as evolutionary adaptations over generations. Here’s why these particular behaviors might vary across various animal types compared to human behavior patterns:

1) Physical Capabilities: Some animals possess unique physiological traits which allow them to manipulate objects easily. Woodpeckers don't actually carry sticks or other materials; instead, instinctively peck holes into bark until they find soft areas filled with food sources such as grubs.
